{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415160"},"attributes":{"position":48,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:06:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:06:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11959"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512811"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11959"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"11959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11959"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.94,0.02,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96665"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4551"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79300"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"89"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1901"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33144"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96665"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-month history of progressively worsening headache. The pain is not better or worse at any time of the day, and at its worst is described as 8/10 in severity. She also reports fatigue, neck and shoulder stiffness and pain, as well as lateral hip pain that she attributes to her history of hip osteoarthritis. She has noticed her right eye vision has been deteriorating recently and thinks she may need new prescription glasses. She denies any previous history of headaches. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history includes hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include perindopril and hormone replacement therapy for menopausal symptoms. On examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 87/min, blood pressure 130/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 13/min, SpO\u2082 99% on room air, and temperature 37.7\u00b0C. Her temporal arteries are tender to palpation bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tension headache","Giant cell arteritis","Optic neuritis","Meningitis","Cluster headache"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiant cell arteritis (GCA)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this patient over 50 years with new-onset headache, temporal artery tenderness, visual disturbance, and symptoms suggestive of polymyalgia rheumatica (PMR). GCA is a vasculitis affecting medium-large vessels, particularly cranial arteries. The visual symptoms represent an ophthalmological emergency requiring immediate high-dose steroids to prevent permanent vision loss. PMR, which affects 40-60% of GCA patients, presents with shoulder, neck and hip girdle pain and stiffness as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETension headache\u003C/strong\u003E is classically described as a band-like headache that is worse at the end of the day or in periods of high stress. It does not typically present with eye symptoms and certainly not with symptoms of PMR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptic neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation of the optic nerve which may be idiopathic in origin or the result of demyelinating disease such as multiple sclerosis. This typically presents peri-orbital or retro-orbital pain, loss of visual acuity and/or colour vision loss. This is a differential that should definitely be considered in this case. It does not fit as well as GCA in this case due to the presence of PMR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E, or inflammation of the meningeal layers of the brain, should always be considered in a patient presenting to the emergency department with a headache a fever as it is a \u0027red-flag\u0027 condition that is life-threatening. Symptoms of meningitis include acute onset headache, fever, photophobia, neck stiffness, nausea/vomiting, altered mental status and +/- petechial / purpuric rash. As the patient has described these symptoms as occurring for two months, this is less likely to be the correct diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECluster headache\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with severe, unilateral periorbital pain lasting 15-180 minutes, occurring in clusters with multiple attacks per day for weeks to months. Associated symptoms include ipsilateral autonomic features such as lacrimation, rhinorrhoea, ptosis, and miosis. The patient\u0027s presentation with bilateral temporal artery tenderness, visual disturbance, and PMR symptoms is inconsistent with cluster headache.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Giant cell arteritis is a vasculitis affecting medium to large vessels, commonly presenting with headache, scalp tenderness, and visual disturbances in patients over 50 years of age.","Visual symptoms in giant cell arteritis represent an ophthalmological emergency requiring immediate high-dose steroid therapy to prevent permanent vision loss.","Polymyalgia rheumatica frequently coexists with giant cell arteritis, presenting as shoulder, neck and hip girdle pain and stiffness."],"references":["Headache Classification Committee of the International Headache Society (IHS) The International Classification of Headache Disorders, 3rd edition. Cephalalgia. 2018 Jan;38(1):1-211. doi: 10.1177/0333102417738202. PMID: 29368949. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29368949/","Gonzalez-Gay MA, Barros S, Lopez-Diaz MJ, Garcia-Porrua C, Sanchez-Andrade A, Llorca J. Giant cell arteritis: disease patterns of clinical presentation in a series of 240 patients. Medicine (Baltimore). 2005 Sep;84(5):269-276. doi: 10.1097/01.md.0000180042.42156.d1. PMID: 16148727. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16148727/","Balcer LJ. Clinical practice. Optic neuritis. N Engl J Med. 2006 Mar 23;354(12):1273-80. doi: 10.1056/NEJMcp053247. PMID: 16554529."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79300"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11959"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79300"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T15:32:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T15:32:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4551"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96665"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou